description:
ABSTRACT   

  &nbsp;  
  This study investigated the effectiveness of the Reading Plan Method in improving the reading comprehension of Grade 3 learners at Yugno Elementary School. A mixed-method research design was employed, allowing the collection of quantitative data on learners&rsquo; reading proficiency and qualitative insights from performance records to provide a comprehensive understanding of the intervention&rsquo;s impact. Using purposive sampling, 10 Grade 3 learners who actively participated in the Reading Plan Method were selected. Quantitative data were analyzed using mean scores, percentages, and a paired sample t-test to determine learners&rsquo; reading comprehension levels before and after the intervention, while qualitative data from document analysis explored the implications of the method on learner engagement, autonomy, and proficiency. Findings revealed that prior to the intervention, most learners were at the Instructional and Frustration levels, indicating a need for guided, strategy-based reading instruction. After implementing the Reading Plan Method, 90% of learners reached the independent level, demonstrating significant improvements in comprehension, fluency, and reading confidence. The paired t-test confirmed that the improvements were statistically significant, validating the method&rsquo;s effectiveness. Document analysis further indicated that the Reading Plan Method is learner-centered, addresses learning gaps, and promotes active engagement with texts. These results suggest that structured, evidence-based reading strategies can enhance reading proficiency and foster independent, strategic, and confident readers.  
  &nbsp;  
  Keywords:      Reading Plan Method, reading comprehension, Grade 3 learners, mixed-method design, learner-centered instruction   
  &nbsp;

